A Czech discovery: an effective substance up to the 'acquired' HIV virus
The team of Czech and German scientists provides evidence of new compounds capable of moderateing the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of this improved substance is that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, such as some available medicines already.
AIDS cannot be cured so far.
However, the life of patients may be prolonged significantly by a mixture of medicines that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the virus replication is not completely removed, the so-called resistant virus will be created; against them, medicines no longer work.
The work of the three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg shows the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that the substances called metal carbrans have an effect on the albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metal carborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way different from all medicines used today, and therefore they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists find new, 'improved' compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus albumin.
Metal carbrans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyedric cages made up of concrete, hydrogen and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A betrayer and resistant virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and it is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, there is no fractionation of the HIV virus and no mature and infectious body cells of the virus would be created.
If we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In an article published in the journal Journal of Medical Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are combined by a short organic series, which remains systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective
The test of the effect of this series of HIV proteases was carried out in practice, and also against its resistant variants, obtained from patients with HIV.
The effect of metallic carboran on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as on the medicinal products that are clinically used, but do not lose its effect on the resistant variants, in which medicines often do not work.
The mechanism of the unique effect, its other qualities such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical changes makes it possible that metal carbourans are interesting components for research with the aim of proposing effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína Rézačová, the head of the laboratory of structural biology at the Institute of Organic and Biochemical Chemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics at the Academy of Sciences.
