Emergency braking aid is already mandatory
As was the case with the anti-lock of ABS brakes and with the control of ESP stability, emergency braking aid systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all small new registrations and commercial vehicles, while for the rest a period of deficiency is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure imposed by the European Union aims to increase the protection of pedestrians, although, in its way of working, it can also help to avoid many in-depth collisions.
The emergency brake assistant does what it does to increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the piotonium that gives the driver.
But this doesn't always keep that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by the Bosch car component manufacturer, the third part of the drivers involved in an accident did not get to tread the brake before collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to an EU study itself, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents could be avoided annually involving pedestrians.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four sinisters would be avoided with damage to persons - when the so-called intelligent emergency braking system is popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects the obstacles and advises the driver, as well as acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps to increase the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if collision is inevitable, the device shall make the maximum effort to minimize damage to the brakes.
